<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-163-896  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 163 896.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 3 1989 v6 n13 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox net technology will help utilize idle resources; Spawn willreduce conflicts for computer time.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Xerox Corp's Palo Alto Research Center announces a computernetwork technology called Spawn, designed to increase efficiencyby reducing idle computer time.andP;  Users are given access to idlecomputers in a network.andP;  When a computer is idle, a message issent throughout the network that it is free.andP;  Users bid for accessto it in accordance with the priority of their transactions.andO;Computer time is granted to the user with the highest priority.andO;The fee for the time is based on the number of users bidding.andO;There is no fee when only one user has made a bid.andP;  Spawn iscurrently being tested on computer networks at DEC and SunMicrosystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. Palo Alto Research Center (innovations).andO;Topic:     New TechniqueResearch and DevelopmentNetwork ManagementIdle Time.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>